(The best normal workflow is:) Tj
T*
T*
(1. Start JARVIS from the launcher) Tj
T*
(2. Let startup complete) Tj
T*
(3. Open the page that matches your work) Tj
T*
(4. Use approval for side-effect actions) Tj
T*
(5. Use `Desktop` or `System` if runtime or voice needs attention) Tj
T*
T*
(### Good page choices) Tj
T*
T*
(? general assistant/operator use: `Dashboard`) Tj
T*
(? coding and repo work: `Workspace`) Tj
T*
(? saved analysis and briefs: `Briefings`) Tj
T*
(? business and queue work: `Operations`) Tj
T*
(? startup/restart/shutdown: `Desktop`) Tj
T*
(? diagnostics and readiness: `System`) Tj
T*
T*
T*
(7. APPROVAL AND SAFETY) Tj
T*
T*
T*
(JARVIS uses approval-based actions for important side effects.) Tj
T*
T*
(That means it is meant to:) Tj
T*
T*
(? prepare actions) Tj
T*
(? stage them clearly) Tj
T*
(? let you approve before execution when needed) Tj
T*
T*
(This is especially important for:) Tj
T*
T*
(? desktop control) Tj
T*
(? workbench commands) Tj
T*
(? coding changes) Tj
T*
(? communication-related actions) Tj
T*
T*
T*
(8. DESKTOP RUNTIME CONTROLS) Tj
T*
T*
T*
(The desktop page is the native lifecycle surface.) Tj
T*
T*
(### Start Runtime) Tj
T*
T*
(Use when the shell is open but backend services are not fully ready.) Tj
T*
T*
(### Restart Runtime) Tj
T*
T*
(Use when:) Tj
T*
T*
(? voice seems stale) Tj
T*
(? backend checks look inconsistent) Tj
T*
(? API behavior feels stuck) Tj
T*
T*
(### Stop Runtime) Tj
T*
T*
(Use when you want the local services to stand down without fully quitting the app window) Tj
T*
1 0 0 1 54 24 Tm
/F1 9 Tf
(JARVIS User Manual   Page 4 of 8) Tj
ET
endstream
